# AI-Generated Adaptive Breadcrumbs — Implementation Plan

## What This Builds
After every command, Groq classifies attacker **intent** in the background. Based on intent, it plants a convincing **fake file (breadcrumb)** in the attacker's current directory. Every breadcrumb is secretly a **canary** — when the attacker opens it, a Critical Threat Event fires instantly in the dashboard. At the end, one click generates a full **Threat Intelligence Report**.

---

## Data Isolation Strategy

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Per-session SQLite files** — each attacker session gets its **own** database file.
> Zero risk of cross-session leakage because sessions literally cannot read each other's files.

```
logs/
├── ghostnet.db                         ← Session index ONLY (session_id, ip, status)
├── sessions/
│   ├── 20250313_134500.db              ← Session A: commands, canaries, intents
│   ├── 20250313_140200.db              ← Session B: completely separate
│   └── 20250313_141000.db              ← Session C: completely separate
└── ssh_host_key
```

**Main DB** (`ghostnet.db`) — only holds the sessions registry table:
```sql
sessions (session_id PK, client_ip, username, start_time, end_time, status)
```

**Per-session DB** (`sessions/<session_id>.db`) — holds everything about ONE attacker:
```sql
commands     (id, timestamp, command, response, execution_time_ms)
intents      (id, timestamp, intent_type, confidence, trigger_command)
canary_files (id, filepath, intent, planted_at, triggered, triggered_at)
threat_events(id, timestamp, event_type, severity, data JSON)
```

